00:07:20.570 --> 00:07:22.960
So clearly, there's
a huge opportunity

00:07:22.960 --> 00:07:24.550
which cannot be ignored.

00:07:24.550 --> 00:07:26.450
But the next question is,
what does it entail?

00:07:26.450 --> 00:07:29.230
How do I make use of
this opportunity?

00:07:29.230 --> 00:07:31.820
What you need to do to make this
happen, the two things

00:07:31.820 --> 00:07:34.350
that you need are
internationalization and

00:07:34.350 --> 00:07:35.350
localization.

00:07:35.350 --> 00:07:36.320
Internationalization--

00:07:36.320 --> 00:07:39.860
i18n, I followed by 18
characters and N. And

00:07:39.860 --> 00:07:40.570
localization--

00:07:40.570 --> 00:07:43.860
L followed by 10 characters
and N.

00:07:43.860 --> 00:07:45.520
What does internationalization
mean?

00:07:45.520 --> 00:07:49.240
It essentially means designing
and coding to enable support

00:07:49.240 --> 00:07:55.330
for languages, countries, and
cultural differences.

00:07:55.330 --> 00:07:58.650
It includes things like
extracting your strings for

00:07:58.650 --> 00:08:02.620
localization, presenting date,
time, currency, number formats

00:08:02.620 --> 00:08:06.300
in the local relevant form,
sorting in language specific

00:08:06.300 --> 00:08:11.790
ways, able to work on or process
user input in the

00:08:11.790 --> 00:08:12.890
given language.

00:08:12.890 --> 00:08:16.400
It also means handling
bi-directional display in

00:08:16.400 --> 00:08:19.640
Middle Eastern languages,
handling diacritics for

00:08:19.640 --> 00:08:22.060
central European languages,
handling double byte

00:08:22.060 --> 00:08:27.020
characters for East
Asian languages.

00:08:27.020 --> 00:08:28.520
And what is localization?

00:08:28.520 --> 00:08:31.650
Localization is the process of
adapting the look and feel of

00:08:31.650 --> 00:08:35.450
your app for languages,
regions, and culture.

00:08:35.450 --> 00:08:36.700
What does it entail?

00:08:40.190 --> 00:08:43.100
Essentially, it includes things
like translation, local

00:08:43.100 --> 00:08:47.780
defaults, and custom features.

00:08:47.780 --> 00:08:49.290
Let's take an example.

00:08:49.290 --> 00:08:55.120
So what you're looking at is
Google Sites, specifically the

00:08:55.120 --> 00:08:57.900
image upload menu.

00:08:57.900 --> 00:08:58.770
What is wrong here?

00:08:58.770 --> 00:09:01.730
And again, I've given you
a hint right there with

00:09:01.730 --> 00:09:03.430
highlighting the region.

00:09:03.430 --> 00:09:06.510
Anyone knows Arabic here?

00:09:06.510 --> 00:09:09.300
What's wrong?

00:09:09.300 --> 00:09:12.050
Yes.

00:09:12.050 --> 00:09:15.430
Notice how in English, we have
the size of the image-- small,

00:09:15.430 --> 00:09:16.770
medium, or large--

00:09:16.770 --> 00:09:21.700
where translated in Arabic, it
actually became Saturday,

00:09:21.700 --> 00:09:23.850
medium, and then large.

00:09:23.850 --> 00:09:24.600
Why?

00:09:24.600 --> 00:09:25.290
What happened?

00:09:25.290 --> 00:09:26.940
Well, two aspects.

00:09:26.940 --> 00:09:29.340
When this was sent for
translation, the small,

00:09:29.340 --> 00:09:34.340
medium, and large were sent as
separate words and with no

00:09:34.340 --> 00:09:35.840
description being provided.

00:09:35.840 --> 00:09:39.830
And the second, when the
translator got this for

00:09:39.830 --> 00:09:42.830
translation, they had little
context of where these were

00:09:42.830 --> 00:09:43.400
coming from.

00:09:43.400 --> 00:09:47.190
So again, S became Sat,
which essentially was

00:09:47.190 --> 00:09:49.790
translated as Saturday.

00:09:49.790 --> 00:09:52.200
Let's take few more examples.

00:09:52.200 --> 00:09:56.330
Here, what you're looking at
is Google Earth mobile app.

00:09:56.330 --> 00:09:59.160
And we are focused in
the Zurich view.

00:09:59.160 --> 00:10:00.410
Anybody from Zurich here?

00:10:03.052 --> 00:10:06.780
Can you tell us what is wrong?

00:10:06.780 --> 00:10:10.150
Notice how the two places, the
names of the two places have

00:10:10.150 --> 00:10:11.720
been garbled.

00:10:11.720 --> 00:10:16.350
The non-ASCII characters have
been removed, specifically the

00:10:16.350 --> 00:10:21.580
u with the umlaut is not being
displayed correctly.

00:10:21.580 --> 00:10:24.330
This is clearly an example of
an internationalization, or

00:10:24.330 --> 00:10:29.110
i18n, issue where the text has
not been rendered correctly.

00:10:29.110 --> 00:10:31.720
When we talked to the engineers
and tried to find

00:10:31.720 --> 00:10:35.770
out what happened, the real
issue was that third party

00:10:35.770 --> 00:10:39.940
JSON library was being
leveraged to do

00:10:39.940 --> 00:10:44.410
deserialization of
the JSON file.

00:10:44.410 --> 00:10:47.430
And that did not handle the
escaping characters in

00:10:47.430 --> 00:10:49.070
meaningful ways.

00:10:49.070 --> 00:10:51.650
So here was an example of
internationalization.

00:10:51.650 --> 00:10:53.850
Let's look at another
example of--

00:10:53.850 --> 00:10:58.760
here, we are talking about
Google Maps in Swedish.

00:10:58.760 --> 00:11:01.900
And on the on the left-hand
side, you also see the

00:11:01.900 --> 00:11:04.860
corresponding English
version as well.

00:11:04.860 --> 00:11:09.700
I'll tell you a little bit more
background on this one.

00:11:09.700 --> 00:11:15.780
A phenomenon that we saw was
in Sweden, specifically

00:11:15.780 --> 00:11:19.490
driving direction functionality,
we were seeing

00:11:19.490 --> 00:11:23.970
about 10% to 15% less usage of
that functionality compared to

00:11:23.970 --> 00:11:27.560
nearby places, compared to all
our average worldwide.

00:11:27.560 --> 00:11:29.590
And we wanted to understand
what is happening.

00:11:29.590 --> 00:11:32.520
So we put an engineer in
Mountain View for about a week

00:11:32.520 --> 00:11:34.750
to try to find what
is happening.

00:11:34.750 --> 00:11:38.500
This person essentially, very
smart engineer, went through

00:11:38.500 --> 00:11:40.980
all the algorithms that we're
using for driving directions

00:11:40.980 --> 00:11:42.830
and how we are pulling them.

00:11:42.830 --> 00:11:46.270
They looked at all our data
sources in terms local data

00:11:46.270 --> 00:11:48.330
and displaying the
street names and

00:11:48.330 --> 00:11:49.450
all of those correctly.

00:11:49.450 --> 00:11:53.410
And it turned out, yes, all of
that was being done correctly.

00:11:53.410 --> 00:11:56.522
Anyone know Swedish here?

00:11:56.522 --> 00:11:58.560
Can you tell what might
have been wrong?

00:12:01.130 --> 00:12:05.980
And the problem was the Get
Direction as in English was

00:12:05.980 --> 00:12:10.160
translated as Instructions
in Swedish.

00:12:10.160 --> 00:12:12.990
And again, as a Google Map user,
when I see instruction,

00:12:12.990 --> 00:12:15.640
I would not really think of
getting driving directions

00:12:15.640 --> 00:12:18.180
based on seeing that
instruction.

00:12:18.180 --> 00:12:20.000
And that really what happened.

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:23.040
When we changed that to really
mean get direction in Swedish,

00:12:23.040 --> 00:12:27.610
we suddenly saw a sudden jump in
terms of the usage for the

00:12:27.610 --> 00:12:28.550
functionality.

00:12:28.550 --> 00:12:31.870
And then, it became on par
with other regions in the

00:12:31.870 --> 00:12:33.520
world as well.

00:12:33.520 --> 00:12:36.940
So what we want to highlight
from these examples is that

00:12:36.940 --> 00:12:40.990
the user experience is impacted
in a big way by how

00:12:40.990 --> 00:12:42.910
you do internationalization
and localization

00:12:42.910 --> 00:12:44.160
implementation.

00:12:46.080 --> 00:12:50.360
So we have talked about what
i18n is, what localization is.

00:12:50.360 --> 00:12:52.490
But the next question is
what do I need to do?

00:12:52.490 --> 00:12:54.840
What does it really
mean for me?

00:12:54.840 --> 00:12:57.480
So let's talk a little bit about
a globalized application

00:12:57.480 --> 00:13:00.650
architecture or the design in
terms of how you will design

00:13:00.650 --> 00:13:04.710
your application in meaningful
ways to make it happen.

00:13:04.710 --> 00:13:09.030
First is your application or
your common code base.

00:13:09.030 --> 00:13:11.980
And that would essentially be
common across all countries.

00:13:11.980 --> 00:13:15.530
It would contain the code
of your functionality.

00:13:15.530 --> 00:13:17.090
And this would be language
neutral.

00:13:17.090 --> 00:13:18.780
This is where all your
key algorithms and

00:13:18.780 --> 00:13:20.220
everything would go.

00:13:20.220 --> 00:13:22.430
The next set, which you would
essentially separate out in

00:13:22.430 --> 00:13:26.230
meaningful ways, is the
globalization services.

00:13:26.230 --> 00:13:28.590
Anything that is
language-dependent, so it

00:13:28.590 --> 00:13:32.130
could be things like handling
of date, time, currencies,

00:13:32.130 --> 00:13:36.730
displaying them correctly,
extraction, anything which is

00:13:36.730 --> 00:13:39.260
language-dependent would
essentially fall under here.

00:13:39.260 --> 00:13:42.220
And you would essentially use
different libraries to handle

00:13:42.220 --> 00:13:43.660
them effectively.

00:13:43.660 --> 00:13:46.000
The next set is the
locale data.

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:48.670
So essentially, it's important
to separate localizable

00:13:48.670 --> 00:13:51.280
resources from your
main code base.

00:13:51.280 --> 00:13:56.300
So examples of localizable
resources would be text,

00:13:56.300 --> 00:13:57.730
images, and so on.

00:13:57.730 --> 00:14:00.050
So notice here how the English,
Japanese, and French

00:14:00.050 --> 00:14:01.710
version are all separated out?

00:14:01.710 --> 00:14:04.720
So if you were to use, for
example, Java, you would

00:14:04.720 --> 00:14:07.790
essentially use the resource
bundles to handle these

00:14:07.790 --> 00:14:09.570
language sources.

00:14:09.570 --> 00:14:12.430
And having those separated
makes it easy for

00:14:12.430 --> 00:14:14.090
localization as well.

00:14:14.090 --> 00:14:16.910
And then, finally, is the
plug-in, which essentially,

00:14:16.910 --> 00:14:18.810
think of that as a
custom feature

00:14:18.810 --> 00:14:21.250
for your local markets.

00:14:21.250 --> 00:14:23.160
Why is that important?

00:14:23.160 --> 00:14:26.570
It really brings the wow
factor for your app.

00:14:26.570 --> 00:14:30.430
Think of like we had the
transit app in German.

00:14:30.430 --> 00:14:33.630
And when we introduced German
train schedules, that really

00:14:33.630 --> 00:14:37.570
made people feel, wow, this
app has been made for me

00:14:37.570 --> 00:14:41.990
rather than something which will
just ported over from US

00:14:41.990 --> 00:14:44.230
with some cosmetic changes.

00:14:44.230 --> 00:14:47.590
Another example is we introduced
cricket scores on

00:14:47.590 --> 00:14:48.930
Google News in India.

00:14:48.930 --> 00:14:52.150
When we did that on the days
when the cricket match was on,

00:14:52.150 --> 00:14:55.310
we saw about 8% to 10% increase
in daily traffic.

00:14:55.310 --> 00:14:56.080
Why?

00:14:56.080 --> 00:14:58.600
People were able to
essentially-- again, cricket

00:14:58.600 --> 00:15:02.910
and Bollywood are pretty
popular in India.

00:15:02.910 --> 00:15:06.900
And people would essentially
come and see those scores on

00:15:06.900 --> 00:15:11.650
Google News when the game
was on those days.

00:15:11.650 --> 00:15:13.780
So here is the complete
picture of

00:15:13.780 --> 00:15:14.760
internationalization.

00:15:14.760 --> 00:15:17.800
It is how you would typically
do your internationalization

00:15:17.800 --> 00:15:20.710
from a design perspective and
how you would have your

00:15:20.710 --> 00:15:23.080
different parts of your code
base separated out in

00:15:23.080 --> 00:15:25.970
meaningful ways so that you can
essentially then extend in

00:15:25.970 --> 00:15:29.370
meaningful ways and make your
code base ready for

00:15:29.370 --> 00:15:31.930
localization.

00:15:31.930 --> 00:15:34.720
Now, let's look at some of the
available tools that will help

00:15:34.720 --> 00:15:36.700
you to make this happen.

00:15:36.700 --> 00:15:39.360
Here are some tools that
are listed for

00:15:39.360 --> 00:15:40.230
internationalization.

00:15:40.230 --> 00:15:42.870
Some of these tools, we are
actively working on.

00:15:42.870 --> 00:15:45.090
Some of these tools, we actively
contribute to.

00:15:45.090 --> 00:15:48.530
But in either of those
scenarios, these are the exact

00:15:48.530 --> 00:15:51.190
same tools that we use
at Google for our

00:15:51.190 --> 00:15:52.640
internationalization as well.

00:15:52.640 --> 00:15:54.910
So the first is the
ICU, International

00:15:54.910 --> 00:15:56.810
Component for Unicode.

00:15:56.810 --> 00:16:00.100
Think of that as a hidden
gold mine for you.

00:16:00.100 --> 00:16:02.980
It really provides you the right
libraries in various

00:16:02.980 --> 00:16:03.850
programming languages--

00:16:03.850 --> 00:16:05.890
C/C++, Java--

00:16:05.890 --> 00:16:08.460
for you to handle Unicode
and globalization

00:16:08.460 --> 00:16:09.700
in meaningful ways.

00:16:09.700 --> 00:16:13.660
So you can handle things like
date, time, currency,

00:16:13.660 --> 00:16:17.340
formatting, and much more
using this library.

00:16:17.340 --> 00:16:22.160
The next library is the
libphonenumber library.

00:16:22.160 --> 00:16:24.270
It essentially handles
the international

00:16:24.270 --> 00:16:26.240
phone numbers for you.

00:16:26.240 --> 00:16:32.770
It essentially incorporates all
world regions, so things

00:16:32.770 --> 00:16:34.590
like area code, country
codes, and all of

00:16:34.590 --> 00:16:35.730
the intricacies involved.

00:16:35.730 --> 00:16:38.860
It essentially encapsulates all
of that and gives you a

00:16:38.860 --> 00:16:42.310
simple interface by which you
can essentially do parsing,

00:16:42.310 --> 00:16:45.850
formatting, storing, and
validating of phone numbers

00:16:45.850 --> 00:16:47.650
across any region
in the world.

00:16:47.650 --> 00:16:51.680
And again, pretty powerful
in respect to that.

00:16:51.680 --> 00:16:55.500
In terms of JavaScript, the
Google Web Toolkit and closure

00:16:55.500 --> 00:16:57.630
tools provide
internationalization support

00:16:57.630 --> 00:16:58.860
for JavaScript.

00:16:58.860 --> 00:17:01.730
We're extending that support
using the ECMAScript standard

00:17:01.730 --> 00:17:03.370
process for that as well.

00:17:06.079 --> 00:17:10.599
For input, research has clearly
showed that users tend

00:17:10.599 --> 00:17:13.119
to use an app more if they're
able to input

00:17:13.119 --> 00:17:14.760
in their own language.

00:17:14.760 --> 00:17:17.819
And that's where Google Input
Tools, a Chrome extension

00:17:17.819 --> 00:17:20.060
