00:40:34.150 --> 00:40:36.380
understand the structure of the
application and where the

00:40:36.380 --> 00:40:39.200
files sit in the application,
all of that information.

00:40:39.200 --> 00:40:42.130
So we're trying to make it
as easy as possible for

00:40:42.130 --> 00:40:45.360
developers and for translators
to do their job without

00:40:45.360 --> 00:40:48.320
needing to understand each
other's roles as much.

00:40:48.320 --> 00:40:51.350
So given that, all the developer
needs to do upon

00:40:51.350 --> 00:40:54.350
coming to the system is add the
resource files from their

00:40:54.350 --> 00:40:57.190
application, from whatever
framework they've been using.

00:40:57.190 --> 00:41:00.440
So we support Java properties
files, Ruby on Rails YAML

00:41:00.440 --> 00:41:03.500
files, a number of other file
formats from popular

00:41:03.500 --> 00:41:05.490
frameworks, and are continuing
to add more

00:41:05.490 --> 00:41:07.660
files as we go along.

00:41:07.660 --> 00:41:11.990
And then, choose the languages
that the developer wants their

00:41:11.990 --> 00:41:13.310
app to be translated into.

00:41:13.310 --> 00:41:16.030
So in this case, we've chosen
Arabic, Chinese,

00:41:16.030 --> 00:41:17.980
Spanish, and Thai.

00:41:17.980 --> 00:41:20.650
And then, the last step from a
developer's perspective is to

00:41:20.650 --> 00:41:22.250
add collaborators
to that project.

00:41:22.250 --> 00:41:25.200
So decide who you want to come
help you translate this.

00:41:25.200 --> 00:41:27.840
It could be friends or family
who speak other languages and

00:41:27.840 --> 00:41:29.760
have offered to help
translate.

00:41:29.760 --> 00:41:32.860
It could be community members
or members of your user base

00:41:32.860 --> 00:41:34.230
who offered to help
translate your

00:41:34.230 --> 00:41:35.910
application to their language.

00:41:35.910 --> 00:41:38.580
Or it could be professional
translators who you decided to

00:41:38.580 --> 00:41:42.170
hire to come in and translate
your application in your first

00:41:42.170 --> 00:41:43.910
international launch to
five languages or

00:41:43.910 --> 00:41:45.860
something of that nature.

00:41:45.860 --> 00:41:48.660
So after adding collaborators
and the translators, the

00:41:48.660 --> 00:41:50.350
developer's job is effectively
done here.

00:41:50.350 --> 00:41:53.300
They don't need to understand
what happens after that point.

00:41:53.300 --> 00:41:57.530
But if you want to, you can go
into that part of the process.

00:41:57.530 --> 00:41:59.120
And we'll show you a little
bit of what that

00:41:59.120 --> 00:42:00.250
looks like as well.

00:42:00.250 --> 00:42:03.560
So when a translator gets an
invitation to come in and work

00:42:03.560 --> 00:42:06.510
on a translation project for
any of the apps that

00:42:06.510 --> 00:42:10.730
developers might upload here,
what they'll see is the actual

00:42:10.730 --> 00:42:14.420
translation interface where we
basically laid out all of the

00:42:14.420 --> 00:42:18.230
messages that need to be
translated and kind of

00:42:18.230 --> 00:42:20.790
abstracted away all of the
different files those came

00:42:20.790 --> 00:42:23.040
from, where they sit
in the application.

00:42:23.040 --> 00:42:26.450
And the translator can just go
ahead and enter translations

00:42:26.450 --> 00:42:28.360
as they go along.

00:42:28.360 --> 00:42:30.480
A few other features that make
this a little bit more

00:42:30.480 --> 00:42:33.010
convenient is we've also
abstracted away the individual

00:42:33.010 --> 00:42:35.310
placeholder support
for each language.

00:42:35.310 --> 00:42:39.440
So a translator can use
placeholders without needing

00:42:39.440 --> 00:42:42.330
to understand how the
programming language that was

00:42:42.330 --> 00:42:45.650
used actually implements
placeholders.

00:42:45.650 --> 00:42:48.990
And we just go ahead when the
developer comes back to export

00:42:48.990 --> 00:42:51.390
the file and replace it with
the placeholders that that

00:42:51.390 --> 00:42:53.500
language is using.

00:42:53.500 --> 00:42:56.350
Another thing that's convenient,
particularly for

00:42:56.350 --> 00:42:59.910
application translation, is the
suggestions feature, which

00:42:59.910 --> 00:43:02.850
allows us to offer suggestions
both from Google Translate,

00:43:02.850 --> 00:43:05.000
but also from previous
translations within that

00:43:05.000 --> 00:43:06.970
application or within
that project.

00:43:06.970 --> 00:43:10.410
So if you have a number of
translators coming in, and the

00:43:10.410 --> 00:43:12.510
word photos has been translated
somewhere earlier

00:43:12.510 --> 00:43:15.530
on, but you now have a new
phrase in the application,

00:43:15.530 --> 00:43:19.860
view my photos, then that
translator will get a preview,

00:43:19.860 --> 00:43:23.400
a suggestion, of what word to
use there so that you maintain

00:43:23.400 --> 00:43:27.670
a consistent translation
throughout the entire project.

00:43:27.670 --> 00:43:30.450
The most important thing that
we found when looking at why

00:43:30.450 --> 00:43:33.940
applications are very different
from static files

00:43:33.940 --> 00:43:35.960
and from other types of content
that you might want to

00:43:35.960 --> 00:43:39.120
localize is that applications
have very short UI strings.

00:43:39.120 --> 00:43:41.570
And so it's very difficult
to get a sense of what an

00:43:41.570 --> 00:43:45.080
individual string or message
might mean for a translator,

00:43:45.080 --> 00:43:48.930
which leads to issues like
Manish described before.

00:43:48.930 --> 00:43:50.830
Small, medium, and
large becomes

00:43:50.830 --> 00:43:52.990
Saturday, medium, and large.

00:43:52.990 --> 00:43:54.890
These sorts of things stem
from translators not

00:43:54.890 --> 00:43:58.870
understanding what a message
is supposed to be in the

00:43:58.870 --> 00:44:00.120
actual application.

00:44:00.120 --> 00:44:03.130
So what we worked hard to do
is make sure that we give

00:44:03.130 --> 00:44:06.090
developers the ability to
capture very easily the

00:44:06.090 --> 00:44:09.260
context of their application
and to capture snapshots so

00:44:09.260 --> 00:44:13.720
that the translator can
translate in context exactly

00:44:13.720 --> 00:44:18.740
what the message means and can
see in real-time how that

00:44:18.740 --> 00:44:22.680
impacts what the message
looks like in the UI.

00:44:22.680 --> 00:44:25.195
A couple of other very
convenient aspects of this

00:44:25.195 --> 00:44:27.990
that help the localization
process significantly is that

00:44:27.990 --> 00:44:31.540
the developer can come through
after the fact and take a look

00:44:31.540 --> 00:44:35.160
at all messages that have or
haven't been translated and

00:44:35.160 --> 00:44:38.360
get a sense of everything looks
fine in Chinese except

00:44:38.360 --> 00:44:40.430
there's this English word over
here that's still in English.

00:44:40.430 --> 00:44:42.970
So clearly I missed something
when I was putting things into

00:44:42.970 --> 00:44:44.820
my resource bundles.

00:44:44.820 --> 00:44:47.860
The other thing that's somewhat
nice about this is a

00:44:47.860 --> 00:44:52.990
developer can come back to this
UI if they want to after

00:44:52.990 --> 00:44:57.020
the translation is complete and
can see the impact that

00:44:57.020 --> 00:44:58.860
the translation has on the UI.

00:44:58.860 --> 00:45:02.480
Because the process we used to
capture the messages from the

00:45:02.480 --> 00:45:05.550
application not only captures
the HTML and the actual

00:45:05.550 --> 00:45:07.620
snapshot, but it also
captures the CSS.

00:45:07.620 --> 00:45:09.640
So we actually have the
style information.

00:45:09.640 --> 00:45:13.390
And you can see in real-time
what happens when a particular

00:45:13.390 --> 00:45:15.050
message breaks the UI.

00:45:15.050 --> 00:45:18.320
In this case, a very long
message might push some of

00:45:18.320 --> 00:45:21.300
these items onto the next line
which would break the UI and

00:45:21.300 --> 00:45:22.440
break the CSS.

00:45:22.440 --> 00:45:24.750
So the developer can get a sense
of where problems are in

00:45:24.750 --> 00:45:27.130
their interface and can fix
those problems before

00:45:27.130 --> 00:45:30.200
redeploying the app
in new languages.

00:45:30.200 --> 00:45:32.560
So this is something that we're
continuing to work on

00:45:32.560 --> 00:45:35.210
and are looking forward to
making available publicly in

00:45:35.210 --> 00:45:37.492
the near future.

